Use MAUI's `Window` lifecycle events with `Preferences` for lightweight storage:

```csharp
// In your ContentPage code-behind
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        // Restore draft
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        // Save draft
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }
}
```

To also catch the **app backgrounding** (e.g. user presses Home without navigating away):

```csharp
// In App.xaml.cs — override CreateWindow
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
    {
        // App went to background — save draft
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            Preferences.Set("note_draft", page.NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    };

    window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
    {
        // App came back — restore draft
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            page.NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get("note_draft", string.Empty);
    };

    return window;
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Preferences`** — simple key-value store, persists across app restarts. Good for small text. For large drafts, use `File.WriteAllTextAsync` instead.
- **`window.Deactivated`** — fires when the app loses focus (home button, app switcher).
- **`window.Resumed`** — fires when the app returns to the foreground.
- **`OnAppearing`/`OnDisappearing`** — covers in-app navigation.
- Clear the draft with `Preferences.Remove(DraftKey)` after the user explicitly saves.
